{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Translator profile importance scores",
    "content": "1: 10 -- Non-negotiable. The source text is Chinese; the target is English. Without native-level command of both, everything else is moot.\n2: 9 -- The essays are philosophy, not literature. A literary translator without philosophical training will flatten the arguments.\n3: 8\n4: 6 -- Essential for K1策略 and 范畴论与境, but those are 2 of 8 essays. A translator who can handle LaTeX notation and knows basic category theory vocabulary (functor, morphism, natural transformation, universal property) is sufficient. Deep mathematical expertise is not required -- the notation mostly needs to be preserved as-is.\n5: 9 -- This collection's register range is extreme. 西西弗斯、班与猫 is casual and conversational; 后形而上学 is dense philosophical German-style prose; K1策略 is mathematical; 零散想法 is aphoristic. A translator who can only do one register will fail on the others.\n6: 8\n7: 9 -- As I argued in my updated report, the essays function as philosophical experiments. The experiential gradient in 西西弗斯、班与猫 (Sisyphus -> office worker -> entrepreneur -> cat) and the gestalt reversal in the 道德仁义礼 passage are not rhetorical decoration but the philosophical argument itself. A translator who reorganizes for English \"flow\" will destroy the experiment.\n8: 8 -- Important for the essays that directly engage Camus, Heidegger, and Nietzsche (西西弗斯、班与猫, 后形而上学, 诗意, 零散想法). The translation should resonate with established English idiom for these thinkers.\n9: 4 -- Buddhist concepts appear but are not central to most essays. The 境 term has Buddhist resonances but the author uses it in a novel way that departs from Buddhist usage. A translator's note can handle the Buddhist chain; the translator does not need deep expertise here.\n10: 5 -- Kantian terminology appears in 零散想法 (the author mentions a possible \"other kind of Kantian question\") but is not structurally central. Basic familiarity sufficient.\n11: 3 -- Analytic philosophy of language register is relevant only to K1策略's language game discussion, and even there the author's approach is more Continental than Analytic. The Wittgenstein references are to the later, more Continental-friendly Wittgenstein. Brandom/Anscombe register is not needed."
  }
}
